<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Company News: Cariplo aims to raise L2,000bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Cariplo, Italy's biggest savings bank, is to place up to 22 per cent of its
capital on the stock market, in a move which could eventually raise between
L2,000bn (Dollars 1.23bn) and L3,000bn for the bank.
The bank - formally known as Cassa di Risparmio delle Provincie Lombarde -
announced last night it wanted to launch the first tranche of a two-stage
capital increase and flotation before the year-end.
Bank officials said the operation would give Milan-based Cariplo, which has
belonged to a public-sector charitable foundation since 1816, the same
flexibility to expand as its quoted competitors in Italy and Europe. The
foundation's shareholders will be asked to approve the operation on April
29.
The total amount raised by Cariplo will almost certainly top the L1,525bn
flotation of 20 per cent of Istituto Bancario San Paolo di Torino, Italy's
biggest banking group, in 1992. Both flotations have been prompted by the
1990 reforms of the Italian banking system, allowing public-sector banks to
restructure and seek share quotations.
Cariplo plans to issue up to 600m new shares before the end of this year.
The bank said the price would be based on the book value of the bank's
equity, discounted for expected dividends, following comparisons with the
value of other Italian and European bank stock.
In the second stage, Cariplo intends to issue 400m subordinated bonds by
June 30, 1995, with warrants for the same number of new shares attached.
Holders will be able to exercise the warrants, at a price based on the
average quoted value of the shares before the offer, after January 1, 1996.
This will spread the impact of the flotation over several years. The Cariplo
board said it would seek authorisation to quote the shares, bonds and
warrants on the domestic and foreign markets.
Cariplo came under the judicial spotlight in February when Mr Roberto
Mazzotta, the group's chairman, resigned after being charged with
corruption. The charges related to allegedly phoney property transactions by
Cariplo's substantial pension fund, and alleged illicit funding of the
Christian Democrat and Socialist parties, which were the bank's main
political influence.
</TEXT>
