<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / International Company News: Peugeot Citroen slides FFr1.4bn
into red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Peugeot Citroen, the French vehicles group, plunged into a net loss of
FFr1.41bn (Dollars 242m) last year, compared with a profit of FFr3.37bn in
1992, the company announced yesterday.
Mr Jacques Calvet, chairman, said that the loss, although smaller than many
analysts had expected, reflected the impact of the 'worst decline in the
European automobile market since the second world war'.
He also blamed a period of 'monetary anarchy' which had seen substantial
currency devaluations for foreign rivals in the UK, Italy and Spain.
According to Mr Calvet, the devaluations of the pound, the lira and the
peseta since 1992 had compounded the fierce competition in the car market.
He also criticised the monetary policy of the French government which, he
said, had resulted in excessively high real interest rates.
Last year's loss was the first at Peugeot Citroen since 1985 and prompted
the group to withhold a dividend.
In spite of last year's reversal, Mr Calvet cited encouraging factors. The
second half of last year showed a marked improvement over the first, with
net losses declining to FFr292m from FFr1.12bn between the two periods.
Mr Calvet said he expected the improvement to continue because of emerging
signs of economic recovery in some of the group's principal markets and a
strong boost to sales in France resulting from government measures. These
measures, which include a payment of FFr5,000 for car owners who trade in a
vehicle more than 10 years old to buy a new one, will help lift new car
sales in the French market to 1.85m this year from 1.72m in 1993, the
company said.
Sales last year fell to FFr145.43bn from FFr155.43bn, while production fell
by 14.5 per cent to 1.75m vehicles. The worst affected markets, according to
Mr Calvet were in continental Europe, with France, Spain, Germany and Italy
all suffering an overall decline of between 18 and 24 per cent.
However, Peugeot Citroen said it had managed to increase its share of the
European market during 1993, to 13.1 per cent in the last three months of
the year from 12 per cent in the first quarter. The company said the
increase reflected the impact of new models.
The improved financial performance in the second half of the year partly
reflected a series of cost-cutting and productivity measures.
</TEXT>
