<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / UK Company News: Cannon Street Pounds 5.5m in the black -
Further disposals under way in move to electronics distribution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cannon Street Investments, the mini-conglomerate, has returned to the black
with a Pounds 5.54m pre-tax profit for the year to January 1, compared with
losses of Pounds 115.5m.
The company has been pruned down from more than 50 small and disparate
businesses into a core of three main divisions, but ultimately it has chosen
to remould itself as an electronics distribution company.
Mr Tom Long, chairman, said that the leisure and food divisions, along with
other remnants of CSI's 1980s buy-all strategy, were effectively up for
sale.
Having undergone significant restructuring, CSI is cash generative and
operating profits are almost double interest costs. It therefore no longer
has to hurry into further sales of non-core assets.
The electronics distribution businesses accounted for Pounds 5.58m (Pounds
1.12m) of CSI's Pounds 8.39m operating profit before Pounds 2.56m of central
costs. Food and drink distribution contributed Pounds 1.35m, but the leisure
division lost Pounds 245,000, because of problems in its time share and tour
business. The hotels remained profitable.
Profits from discontinued businesses amounted to Pounds 839,000 but these
were more than offset by one-off restructuring costs of more than Pounds 1m.
There was a Pounds 2.43m profit from the sale of businesses last year,
primarily PM Tamson, the Georgian House Hotel and Cannon Materials Handling
 -the latter was sold at a loss.
Interest costs fell from Pounds 7.04m to Pounds 2.72m, as a result of debt
reduction and falling interest rates. At the year end, net debt amounted to
about Pounds 25.4m, down from Pounds 42.9m.
The company has restructured its balance sheet to enable it to pay dividends
for the first time since October 1992. It will first have to pay the Pounds
2.5m arrears on its preference dividend, however, and it is taking a
'prudent' view on the resumption of ordinary dividends.
COMMENT
Having sifted through the wreckage of what was once a high-flying
conglomerate, the new management of Cannon Street Investments has found a
worthwhile core. Its electronics distribution division increased profits
fivefold last year, and management plans to build around the Altai
subsidiary. Analysts expect profits to exceed Pounds 7m in the current year,
putting the shares on a p/e of 11.5. This leaves minimal downside for the
shares, while there is considerable upside if it can demonstrate success in
building up its new-found core.
</TEXT>
