<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Vauxhall falls 17% as continental exports suffer: GM arm
still most profitable carmaker in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Vauxhall, the UK subsidiary of General Motors of the US, suffered a 17.3 per
cent fall in pre-tax profits last year to Pounds 185.1m (Pounds 223.7m), but
remained the most profitable carmaker in Britain.
Mr Charles Golden, chairman and managing director, said profits would
recover this year helped by higher sales, increased productivity and further
cost reductions.
Profits were depressed last year by an 18.7 per cent decline in production
of cars and car-derived vans to 245,313, the company said.
Vehicle output fell after a steep decline in exports, which dropped 58 per
cent to 46,964 because of weak demand for new cars in continental Europe.
Vauxhall's two vehicle assembly plants at Luton, Bedfordshire, and at
Ellesmere Port, Cheshire, worked at only 78 per cent capacity last year
compared with 96 per cent in 1992, said Mr Golden.
Vauxhall captured a record 17.1 per cent share of the UK new car market last
year, where it is in second place behind Ford, compared with 16.7 per cent
in 1992. Its UK car sales jumped 14.2 per cent to 303,926 in an overall
market that rose 11.6 per cent to 1.78m. Operating profits fell 23 per cent
to Pounds 191.8m, while turnover rose 3.4 per cent to Pounds 3.1bn.
Mr Golden said that the decline in exports - down by 66,000 vehicles - had
reduced profits by Pounds 71m, while the cut in production had cost another
Pounds 18m. The Luton plant was hit by short-time working and forced to halt
production of the Vauxhall Cavalier/Opel Vectra for nearly 13 weeks in 1993.
These factors had been offset by cost-savings, which improved profitability
by Pounds 36m, and by increased domestic sales which contributed an extra
Pounds 10m.
Mr Golden said Vauxhall had improved its productivity by 88 per cent in the
past six years, from 24 to 45 cars per employee.
The workforce was reduced by 6.7 per cent during the year to 10,222, and it
had been cut to fewer than 10,000 by February this year.
Vauxhall was planning to invest more than Pounds 100m to modernise and
automate its Luton assembly plant in the next two years in preparation for
the launch of the new generation Vauxhall Cavalier/Opel Vectra in late 1995.
Mr Golden was cautious about the outlook for UK new car sales and forecast a
rise of 6-7 per cent for the year to 1.9m. He said Vauxhall expected to
increase its market share further, helped by the launch of the new Omega
executive car, the Monterey four-wheel drive sports/utility vehicle, and the
Tigra small coupe in the autumn.
The Avis Europe group of car rental companies, in which GM holds a 26.5 per
cent interest through Vauxhall, made a net loss of Pounds 74.2m last year.
