<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Babcock issue to raise Pounds 79m amid shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Babcock International, the engi-neering contractor and materials handling
group, yesterday announced a four-for-seven rights issue to raise Pounds
78.6m and the restructuring of its heavily loss-making energy division.
The shake-up will lead to 450 job cuts at Babcock's manufacturing plant at
Renfrew, Scotland, and a Pounds 25m exceptional charge in the year ended
March 31. The group estimated its pre-tax loss at Pounds 41.2m for 1993-94,
against a profit of Pounds 21.1m a year earlier. It is passing its final
dividend.
Both the rights issue and the charges were larger than some analysts had
expected, but Babcock shares rose from 33 1/4 p to 37p as the City reacted
warmly to the long-awaited announcement of future strategy, following the
arrival in October of a new management team.
Mr John Parker, chief executive, said: 'We have put in place a plan to
enable Babcock to be more competitive in the international marketplace. The
overall objective is to establish sustainable profit and dividend growth.'
Babcock has suffered a succession of troubles in its contracting businesses.
The biggest was the discovery of serious technical problems on its Pounds
400m-plus flue gas desulphurisation contract at National Power's Drax power
station in North Yorkshire.
Now Mr Parker plans to move Babcock's energy division away from large
construction activities to become more focused on technology, engineering
and project management. 'We have a certain size, and we must not bet the
balance sheet on a particular contract,' he said.
The division, he said, would concentrate marketing towards higher growth
markets, particularly China and the Pacific Rim. It has signed a partnership
agreement with the Wuhan Boiler Works, China's fourth largest boilermaker.
At the same time, Mr Parker will continue to expand Babcock's materials
handling and process divisions.
Babcock has also negotiated replacement banking facilities totalling Pounds
60m, extending over two years. These are conditional on the rights issue
proceeding and without them, the group would have been in breach of its
banking covenants on publication of the audited accounts for the year ended
March 31.
Lord King will retire as chairman in July. Mr Parker will succeed him and Mr
Nick Salmon, managing director, will become chief executive.
