<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Child Support Agency Pounds 100m short of target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Child Support Agency is more than Pounds 100m short of its overall
target of making benefit savings of Pounds 530m for 1993-94, forcing the
government to alter its business plan and targets for the following year.
The shortfall in savings will hit the performance-related pay bonus of Ms
Ros Hepplewhite, the agency's chief executive.
Whitehall officials stressed that it would be wrong to blame Ms Hepplewhite
for the agency's failure to meet its targets.
Ministers put the agency's disappointing financial performance down to
changes forced by the Commons social security committee and a refusal by
some fathers to pay maintenance.
The Department of Social Security responded to Commons criticism of the
agency by amending the formula for absent parents' maintenance payments in
February.
The changes also allowed fathers facing big bills to pay in stages during an
18-month period.
Officials fear the shortfall in benefit savings could be significantly
higher than Pounds 100m if the figures for April, the last in the agency's
financial year, fail to meet the original target.
In 1992-93, the CSA's forerunner, the Child Support Unit, made benefit
savings of Pounds 313m, while in 1991-92 the Benefit Agency recovered Pounds
283m.
The department has already decided to scale back the agency's business plan
and targets for 1994-95 and subsequent years. 'We do not have a Stalinist
five-year plan,' said one official.
'The subsequent targets will be set in the light of what has been achieved
and is achievable in the future.'
The Commons social security committee will launch a 'thorough review' of the
agency's workings when it receives the CSA's annual report, expected in
July.
Ministers had hoped that any subsequent review of the agency would take
place later in the year. Mr Frank Field, the Labour chairman, was yesterday
adamant, however, that the review would take place immediately on receipt by
the committee of the CSA's report
The social security committee expects to publish its second report on the
agency in the autumn.
After receiving 2,000 letters, Mr Field says he believes the anger expressed
by the public necessitates a new inquiry to decide whether the formula,
which determines how much parents should pay, should be changed.
The review will also consider setting up an appeals tribunal with discretion
on how the formula should be implemented.
'This is the biggest change in the welfare state since its inception in
1945,' said Mr Field. 'If the agency is to be strengthened, it demands a
major review of its workings.'
</TEXT>
