<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Clothes retailers hit as Brussels imposes limits on silk
imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNY LUESBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The imported silk shirt could soon disappear from the British chain store.
Clothes retailers say that harsh import restrictions levelled against
Chinese textiles by the European Commission have left them with millions of
pounds' worth of silk clothing sitting in Asian ports, paid for, but now
unlikely to be delivered.
Until last month there were no limits on silk clothing imports into the UK,
and the market was thriving. The silk shirt, once an expensive specialist
purchase, was on the racks of all the big clothing chains thanks to cheaper
imports from China.
However, Brussels introduced a Europe-wide system of quotas on Chinese
imports not covered under its bilateral trade arrangements, and British
importers say they have already filled this year's European silk quota of
20,000 tonnes.
Trade officials at the Chinese embassy in London protested yesterday that
the quota was introduced without consultation. The low ceiling was set as
the Commission began preparing for wide-ranging market-opening negotiations
with Beijing.
Apparently unaware of the axe that was about to fall, retailers such as
Marks and Spencer, Burtons, C&amp;A, BHS and Sock Shop ordered shirts on which
irrevocable letters of credit were issued.
'It is not just that these items were paid for and now can't be got into the
country, but the level of the quotas is so low that it represents a
scandalous interruption to the flow of trade,' Mr Hugh Clark, the director
of trading policy at the British Retail Consortium, said yesterday.
The Department of Trade and Industry confirmed that licences issued for
Chinese silk imports into the UK had already reached the limit.
In 1992, before the silk boom, European imports were 12,000 tonnes,
according to the Commission, but UK retailers say their imports more than
trebled last year.
'We will be OK for about two months, but then that's it,' said TEL Europe,
silk supplier to the Burton Group and BhS, among others. 'There will
certainly be no silk shirts for the pre-Christmas shopper. And we are
looking at a fall in our business to a third of last year's level.'
The DTI is lobbying hard for an increase to the quotas. But Brussels is
adamant that not only will it not alter this year's quotas, but that the
quotas will stand, subject to negotiations with China.
</TEXT>
