<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Observer: Sabres out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Percy Cradock, the foreign affairs adviser to two prime ministers who
now spends his days advising merchant bankers Kleinwort Benson, has a nice
line in one-liners. He particularly relishes exercising the talent at the
expense of Chris Patten, Hong Kong's governor.
In pursuing confrontation with China over Hong Kong's political development,
Patten has 'taken Hong Kong over the edge', while the Legislative Council
has embarked on a 'legislative Charge of the Light Brigade', in approving
Patten's plans.
When asked if the legislature might not have the right at least to give
democracy a try, Cradock intoned: 'You assert the universal right of
legislatures to commit suicide . . . an interesting proposition.'
