<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / PIA may register individuals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Personal Investment Authority said yesterday that it would consider
whether a system of registering individuals as well as the firms they work
for would be practical.
The move by the new watchdog seems to be an attempt to pre-empt a likely
recommendation from the Commons Treasury committee, which is examining
financial regulation.
Individual registration would enable the authority to discipline specific
sales agents as well as their companies.
While the statement may reassure the committee - which holds its second
session with Mr Joe Palmer, PIA chairman, and Ms Colette Bowe, its chief
executive, next week - it is likely to cause dismay in the industry.
There will be concern over the possible costs of individually registering
all the direct sales forces of life companies.
More immediately, some of the PIA's 6,000 potential members, who have not
yet decided to join, will be worried that the new regulator's goalposts may
be moving when there are already uncertainties about how it will approach
its task.
The regulators which the authority is due to succeed in July differ in
registration practice. Fimbra, the self-regulating organisation for
independent financial advisers, does register individual members but Lautro,
for the life insurance industry, does not. Mr Kit Jebens, Lautro's chief
executive who will be in charge of the PIA's relations with its members,
this week said Lautro had found it better not to undermine companies'
responsibility for their employees.
</TEXT>
