<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Strong retail sales growth at odds with expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strong retail sales growth in March appeared yesterday to contradict earlier
indications that consumers had been tightening their belts before this
month's tax increases.
A survey from the Confederation of British Industry, and a Gallup poll of
consumer confidence, had both hinted that sales growth might be sluggish in
March. But figures from the Central Statistical Office showed that sales
were 0.8 per cent higher than in February.
Analysts suggested that the March figures might have been distorted by the
Easter holidays, which make seasonal adjustment difficult because the
holidays move around the calendar. The effect of Easter on sales is clear
from the value figures, which are not seasonally adjusted. The value of
retail sales in March was 6.5 per cent higher than a year earlier, compared
with a 4.4 per cent annual increase in February.
The annual rate of volume growth jumped from 2.8 per cent in February to 3.8
per cent in March. However Mr Simon Briscoe, UK economist at SG Warburg
Securities, pointed out that the three-monthly trend was more smooth.
Volumes were 3.5 per cent higher in the three months to March than in the
same period a year earlier; in February, on the same basis, the increase was
3.4 per cent.
The strongest growth came from the household goods sector, where sales
volumes were 8.1 per cent higher in the first quarter of 1994, compared with
a year earlier. Volumes in clothing and footwear stores and mixed-retail
businesses were also up strongly. The only sector to show a fall was 'other
non-food', which consists of a wide range of shops from tobacconists to
florists.
</TEXT>
