<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Old failings cloud brighter economic outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If the BBC presenter Martyn Lewis were to produce one of his 'good news'
bulletins on the UK economy, he would have plenty of items.
Unemployment is falling, inflation and interest rates are at their lowest
for more than 20 years, retail sales are growing and companies' investment
intentions are on the increase. Figures for gross domestic product in the
first quarter of this year are certain to show further growth, which will
mean that the recovery has lasted eight quarters, longer than the recession
which preceded it.
But the average British television audience might find such an optimistic
picture hard to believe. Consumer confidence is close to a record low,
according to a Gallup poll published earlier this week.
This discrepancy between headline statistics and the public mood is not too
hard to explain. For a start, consumers are well aware of the impact of this
month's tax increases on their pay packets.
Second, the fall in unemployment still leaves some 2.72m people out of work,
even if one does not believe Labour's claim that the 'real' figure is 5m.
Furthermore, jobs created in the recovery have tended to be part-time or in
small businesses.
The official forecast is for 2.5 per cent growth in GDP this year, following
1.9 per cent in 1993. The problem for the government is that this growth is
not sufficient to create a feel-good factor among the population. During the
'Lawson boom' of the mid-1980s, GDP grew at 4 per cent or more for four
successive years, including a heady 5 per cent in 1988.
Of course the Lawson boom did not turn out well - the current account
deficit widened to Pounds 22.5bn in 1989 and headline inflation accelerated
to double figures during 1990. The authorities, and in particular Mr Eddie
George, the governor of the Bank of England, are anxious to prevent a
recurrence.
But old habits die hard. Britain has continued to run a current account
deficit throughout the recession. In spite of the devaluation in September
1992, the deficit seems to be widening - exporters have exploited the lower
pound by increasing prices rather than sales, while continental European
companies, faced with sluggish domestic economies, are exporting to UK
consumers.
Another traditional UK problem is inflation. Here the news is rather better;
annual underlying inflation fell to 2.4 per cent in March, in the lower half
of the government's target range. Many commentators believe that the UK
economy is still operating well below capacity; this so-called 'output gap'
means that GDP can continue to grow for some time without inflationary
pressures emerging.
However, the government is handicapped by past policy failures. After the
ignominy of sterling's departure from the European exchange rate mechanism
in September 1992, the government has had to work hard to restore its
credibility in the financial markets, necessitating a much more prominent
role for the Bank.
Experience has made financial markets reluctant to believe that Britain can
control inflation. An adverse reaction to the last base rate cut, in
February, may have made the Bank even more cautious about future reductions,
especially while it is possible to find some indicators, such as this week's
average earnings figures, which point to inflationary pressures.
To avoid Britain's old trade and inflationary problems, a sustained recovery
may require a shift from personal consumption, at present at a record high
as a proportion of GDP, towards investment. Unfortunately for the
government, cutting consumption, through taxes or low wage growth, is
unlikely to create a feel-good factor among voters.
</TEXT>
