<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / South-west sees improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies in south-west England are reporting a rise in sales and orders and
improved profitability.
About 70 per cent of companies saw higher turnover in the first quarter of
this year, says the latest survey by Bristol Chamber of Commerce and
Initiative. Only 10 per cent said turnover had fallen. Slightly more than
half said profitability had improved.
'This is a very positive report,' the chamber said.
Its survey, covering 337 companies in the south-west, found businesses in
the manufacturing and service sectors had seen improvements in the domestic
market.
In the export market, nearly half of manufacturers had higher sales and
orders, with only about one in five registering a fall.
Nearly a third of manufacturers and service businesses were increasing their
investment plans, although 70 per cent of companies were operating at below
full capacity.
Companies employing more than 500 people continue to shed staff. Smaller
companies expected employment to remain stable, or in some cases to expand,
in the next quarter.
About a third of companies said cashflow was deteriorating, with smaller
companies suffering most.
