<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Receivers at Lancer Boss announce more job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Receivers for Lancer Boss yesterday announced another 50 redundancies at the
lift-truck maker's Leighton Buzzard plant in Bedfordshire, reducing the
workforce to about 700.
The cuts follow 19 made on April 10, two days after Mr Allan Griffiths and
Mr Scott Barnes of Grant Thornton were appointed administrative receivers of
Lancer Boss's UK operations.
Mr Griffiths also announced that he had reached agreement with the
management of Jungheinrich, the Hamburg-based lift-truck maker, on a
continuing trading relationship between Lancer Boss and Steinbock Boss.
Steinbock Boss is Lancer's former German unit, which Jungheinrich acquired
from the German receiver last Thursday. Lancer Boss and Steinbock Boss are
closely related and a trading relationship is crucial to Mr Griffiths'
attempts to sell Lancer Boss as a going concern.
Mr Griffiths said the trading relationship between the two companies was
'essentially unaltered'.
'Since that trading relationship has traditionally accounted for
approximately 50 per cent of Lancer Boss sales, I am confident that this
will offer substantial comfort to customers, suppliers and potential buyers
of the business,' he said.
He said he planned to begin negotiations to sell the business as a going
concern once prospective purchasers had researched the business and assessed
its value.
On Wednesday, Mr Bob Bischof, chairman of Jungheinrich in the UK, said the
German company expected to be ready to make a bid for Lancer Boss by the
middle of next week. 'We will be looking seriously at acquiring it - that is
our intention,' he said.
Mr Griffiths said yesterday's redundancies followed a comprehensive
assessment, in consultation with the existing management team, of the likely
demand in the marketplace.
Those made redundant were from a cross-section of the workforce.
</TEXT>
