<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Campaign Diary: BCCI ghost returns to haunt islands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The collapse of Bank of Credit and Commerce International is being blamed
for the end of a long tradition of independent politics in the Western
Isles. All 30 Independent members of the Western Isles Council are up for
re-election on May 5, and, for the first time in living memory, Labour is
putting up five candidates.
Calum MacDonald, the islands' Labour MP, says the council needs firmer
direction following the loss of Pounds 24m in the BCCI crash.
But cynical local activists say BCCI is being used to help shore up
MacDonald's shaky majority of 1,703 over the SNP.
The dissidents say the party decided against fielding a full slate of
candidates because of fears that its image would suffer if it had to deal
with the aftermath of the BCCI fiasco. The hope is that five councillors
will be enough to raise the party's profile between parliamentary elections,
without risking too much fall-out from unpopular decisions.
Labour-controlled Bristol City Council is being tackled hard by fans of
Bristol Rovers, which has to play its Division 2 matches at Bath because of
the lack of a stadium in the city. Aggrieved supporters have formed a
Bristol party which is fielding 10 candidates, all in Labour-held wards.
Its chairman Tony Locke, 53, says the party has picked up widespread support
from people who want better leisure and transport. Jim Williams, a former
Labour lord mayor of the city, has dropped plans to stand for the party, but
Graham Robertson, the Labour council leader, is being challenged in his own
ward. Labour, which has a majority of 12, dismisses the Bristol party as
'one of those irritants'.
                           *      *      *
Bill Cash, the Tory arch-Euro-sceptic, will be the main British participant
in a motley gathering of anti-Maastricht campaigners in Paris today, called
to campaign for a 'Europe of nation states'.
Others at the plush George V hotel rally include businessman Sir James
Goldsmith, Lord Rees Mogg, former editor of The Times, Charles de Gaulle, a
conservative (small c) Euro MP who is the grandson of the late French
president, and Manfred Brunner, head of the German anti-Maastricht party.
Somewhat grandiosely, the participants have set themselves the task of
'breaking the monopoly of the Euro-federalists'. Shouldn't be hard to do,
since the latter category seems to contain ever fewer people.
                           *      *      *
Most Conservative Euro candidates have a more pressing problem - how to get
out the vote on June 9.
One go-ahead candidate, aware that Tory workers are less than keen to
support John Major on the doorsteps, has subcontracted his election campaign
to cut out the voluntary middleman. Campaign literature is to be stuffed
into envelopes by a direct-mail marketing company and delivered by
contractors for the local free-sheet newspaper.
Canvassing and 'knocking-up' on the big day is to be done from a telephone
bank instead of on foot. The candidate has not gone completely high-tech,
though. He says he will make at least one personal appearance during the
campaign.
                           *      *      *
Robert Guy, chairman of the London gold fixing and the City's bullion market
association, is campaigning for the Conservatives in a more traditional way
for the Labour-held London West Euro seat. Guy, 50, a non-executive director
of NM Rothschild, has deserted the plush parlours of the City to tour
pensioners' clubs in his rambling constit-uency.
He says voters are less Euro-sceptical than many imagine. 'Most people
understand it would be economic suicide to consider leaving the European
Union. But they are very jealous of their British rights and their national
sense of identity.'
                           *      *      *
So bad is the Conservative party's position in the European elections that
the possibility of a Canadian-style wipeout is becoming a campaign cliche.
Don't expect to hear the Canadian parallel from the lips of politically
aware Labour supporters, though. Canada's socialist New Democrats ended up
with only eight seats, hardly better than the two won by the Progressive
Conservatives.
The winners were the Liberals, now in government, and regional parties like
the Bloc Quebecois and the (western) Reform party. Step forward Plaid Cymru
and the Scottish National party . . .
                           *      *      *
The suggestion that the nation marks the 50th anniversary of D-day by frying
Spam fritters may cost the Conservatives thousands of veterans' votes. But
it has gone down quite well with George A. Hormel &amp; Co, which makes the
chopped pork delicacy in Austin, Minnesota.
Hormel's Alan Krejci, says Spam jokes (the most famous is the Monty Python
'Spam with everything' sketch) have helped make the stuff 'a modern food
icon'. Hormel sells 110m cans a year in the US - 3.8 cans are eaten every
second.
'We have lived with the wartime image for 50 years; it doesn't seem to be
doing us any harm,' says Krejci.
Maybe the PR whizz-kid who thought up the idea was on to something after
all.
</TEXT>
<XX>
