<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Major bows to D-day pounding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday moved to defuse the row over this summer's D-day
anniversary by bowing to the demands of veterans for a bigger say in the
events marking the Normandy landings in June 1944.
As ministers admitted that the government's approach had become a public
relations fiasco, Mr Major sought to assure MPs that the government's
planning would emphasise the commemorative rather than celebratory nature of
the events.
His comments followed an urgent meeting between Mr Peter Brooke, the
heritage secretary, and representatives of the Normandy Veterans Association
and the Royal British Legion.
Mr Brooke, whose department has been employing public relations consultants
Lowe Bell to co-ordinate nationwide activities to mark the invasion, assured
the veterans that the government would not trivialise the anniversary.
In particular, the veterans would be given an important role in the
organisation of a planned jamboree in London's Hyde Park.
The veterans had threatened a boycott but have now agreed to reconsider and
draw up their own suggested programme for the day.
After discussing the debacle at yesterday's cabinet meeting, other ministers
accused Mr Brooke's department of mishandling the anniversary. They said the
government should distance itself from some of the 'frivolous events'
suggested by Lowe Bell.
Under pressure in the Commons from Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, over
ignoring the sensitivities of those who took part in the landings, Mr Major
said the main focus of the programme would be one of solemn commemoration.
He cited an open-air ceremony of remembrance which will be conducted by the
archbishop of Canterbury, religious services in the British cemetery in
Normandy and a march past by veterans.
But the prime minister said the government also wanted to involve the rest
of the country: 'As well as commemorating the bravery and sacrifice of those
who took part in the Normandy campaign, we also wish to remember the immense
effort made by the whole civilian population leading up to D-day and beyond.
That is why we want the commemorations to involve all generations, including
our children.'
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
</TEXT>
