<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / DTI urged to take over training role: Department of
Employment's future bleak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commons trade and industry committee is to recommend the transfer of
responsibility for training from the Department of Employment to the
Department of Trade and Industry. The move will fuel speculation about the
employment department's future.
In a report on UK competitiveness to be published next week, the committee
will single out the short-term culture of the City as one of a number of
structural weaknesses that are damaging Britain's prospects.
However, in conclusions reached as the government puts the finishing touches
to its own competitiveness white paper, the MPs will argue that the decline
in UK manufacturing can still be arrested.
The white paper, which the DTI plans to publish before May 19 - the official
start of the European election campaign - is expected to act as a mid-term
manifesto, pulling together a range of government policies on education,
training and manufacturing.
It should enable Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, to
maintain a high political profile in advance of elections that could have a
critical bearing on the future Tory leadership.
It is generally accepted that a poor Conservative performance would deal a
devastating blow to Mr John Major's premiership.
Next week's report - prepared by a committee with a Conservative majority -
will suggest that the taxation system should be used to try to change the
short-term culture of the City.
It calls for consideration to be given to an adjustment of taxes to make
executive share options less attractive.
The MPs believe these options can be damaging because they give managers an
incentive to keep their company's share price high and discourage them from
cutting dividends, even when this would be in the company's long-term
interest.
They also believe that ministers should consider using tax incentives to
encourage investors to adopt a longer-term approach to investing in small
companies.
The MPs believe that shifting primary responsibility for training to the DTI
is one of a number of measures that could be taken to improve the
effectiveness of government programmes. Such a step would lift the DTI's
annual budget by up to Pounds 2.3bn.
Senior Tory officials have been floating the idea of scrapping the
employment department this summer as part of the expected cabinet reshuffle.
Details of the report emerged as Mr Michael Portillo, the rightwing chief
Treasury secretary, used a speech in London to set out his own agenda for
improving competitiveness.
Pledging to resist pressure for Britain to sign up to the social chapter of
the Maastricht treaty, Mr Portillo said the government had put in place a
framework in which business could flourish.
Britain had stabilised its share of world trade in manufactured goods after
decades of decline, he said. Further improvement depended on 'investment,
education, training and infrastructure'.
</TEXT>
