<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Le cut-price ticket 'by invitation only'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel yesterday unveiled plans for a limited 'by invitation only'
service through the Channel tunnel during the summer months until a full
freight and passenger timetable can be run from October.
The announcement was made as the company unveiled its preliminary annual
report for 1993.
Shareholders, business contacts, long-term supporters of the tunnel, the
travel trade and the press will be offered reduced fares under Eurotunnel's
'overture service'.
The reduced-fare services will start after the official opening on May 6.
The company hopes that 50,000 cars will have gone through the tunnel 'to
create more positive awareness' before full-price tickets go on sale in
October.
However, delays in getting rolling stock into service will mean that the
full programme of four passenger shuttle trains an hour will not be possible
until spring next year.
Eurotunnel is currently carrying out a seven-day series of full-scale tests
running trains through the tunnel.
The company said yesterday that it had negotiated rates with nearly 900
freight customers which account for 80 per cent of the market for
driver-accompanied trucks crossing the Channel. It plans to start its
limited freight shuttle by invitation in May. Invitation passenger shuttles
are due to start in July.
Eurotunnel expects to announce revised projections of traffic levels and
revenues at the time of its rights issue prospectus, due between May 17 and
the end of June. It plans to raise at least Pounds 1.1bn. Equity will
account for less than half the total, but the final figure will depend on
the debt equity mix and sum needed to cover additional interest payments.
Much of Eurotunnel's debt - 60 per cent of sterling debt and 21 per cent of
French debt - was at fixed rates at the end of 1993. The aim is have 75 per
cent of both currencies fixed for four to six years.
Sir Alastair Morton, co-chairman of Eurotunnel, yesterday said the
explanation for delays in opening the tunnel included the need for 4,000
contractors' staff to work alongside Eurotunnel staff after the official
handover in December.
</TEXT>
