<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / E Anglia power plant in doubt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An independent power company appears to have shelved plans to build an
electricity plant in East Anglia following the decision by Offer, the
industry regulator, to put a limit on prices in the electricity wholesale
pool, Michael Smith writes.
Independent Power Generators, a consortium involving French companies, has
terminated a contract with National Grid to take power from a proposed 730MW
station in Sutton Bridge, East Anglia. The company was not available for
comment last night.
It said recently it was deferring non-essential development at Sutton Bridge
'due to continuing downward regulatory pressure of the wholesale price of
electricity and over-capacity in the UK market'.
It added that the National Grid's estimates showed that the excess of
generating capacity over peak demand could reach 42.6 per cent by 2000.
Regional power companies estimated demand for electricity would grow by 1.3
per cent annually to the end of the decade, the company said. A year ago
that estimate had been 1.6 per cent.
