<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Stock Exchange approves order matching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange yesterday cleared the way for a trading system
that will automatically match orders to buy and sell shares.
Approval for the system, known as Seaquence, had been opposed by some of the
exchange's largest members. The system is due to run in parallel with and
compete against the existing market-making system.
Yesterday's vote by the exchange board reverses a controversial decision
last year and authorises funding to build the system. The move is in
response to rising competition from new exchanges.
The order-matching system will automatically pair buy and sell orders for a
share at the same price. Order matching has been used with great success by
Nasdaq, the US-based electronic exchange.
The move to order matching is likely to anger market-makers, most of whom
are among the largest and most wealthy members of the exchange.
Market-makers make firm offers to buy and sell shares at a set price in all
market conditions and earn profits on the difference.
Last June market-makers on the exchange's board had refused to approve plans
to replace the ageing Seaq share-dealing system with one which could
incorporate order matching. The plan was only approved after the exchange
agreed to cut costs and eliminate the order-matching capacity in the new
system - a decision reversed yesterday.
The exchange said yesterday: 'The exchange is 100 per cent behind a
quote-driven (market-making) system'.
The exchange's new chairman, Mr John Kemp-Welch, said he had become
particularly concerned about a new dealing mechanism, Tradepoint, which will
have order matching and market-making capacity, and by threats from venture
capitalists to develop a new exchange to handle dealing in small-company
shares.
Many stock exchange members believe that market-making has failed to produce
the necessary liquidity in small-company shares and that only an
order-matching system will meet investors' needs.
Mr Kemp-Welch said the exchange would not be able to head off the threat of
a small-companies' exchange unless it too offered investors an
order-matching system.
Several weeks ago Mr Michael Lawrence, the newly-appointed chief executive
of the exchange, wrote to exchange members saying that if board members
failed to approve funds to build order matching into Seaquence now, it would
be far more expensive to do so later.
Yesterday's approval applied only to building the software for the system.
A decision about whether to proceed with plans to build hardware will be
made towards the end of next year, the exchange said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
