<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Norwegian medical unit heads for Gorazde
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of a Norwegian medical unit left Sarajevo airport yesterday as part
of a United Nations convoy of 100 troops and 40 medical staff heading for
the besieged Bosnian Moslem enclave around Gorazde, only to be blocked by a
crowd of Serb women demonstrators. In Gorazde itself Serb forces continued
to shell the town, including a makeshift hospital, where about 20 people
were killed, Our Foreign Staff reports.
In Washington, the US yesterday proclaimed its 'strategic interest' in
containing the Bosnian war. Mr Warren Christopher, the secretary of state,
said the US wanted to stop conflict from reigniting in Croatia or starting
in the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia. 'We have a strategic interest
in preventing that war from spreading,' he told Congress, voicing confidence
that European allies would back escalating air strikes when they confer in
Brussels.
In Gorazde 450 people have been killed and 1,500 injured since last month
when Serb forces began their assault.
Bosnia's prime minister, Mr Haris Silajdzic, said the town's Moslem
defenders faced Serb demands that they abandon their remaining pockets of
resistance on the right bank of the town, where the hospital is located. But
local radio stations said the defenders would not surrender.
There were reports last night of hand-to-hand fighting in the town.
UN officials yesterday feared for the fate of 13 UN and humanitarian workers
trapped in Gorazde.
