<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Moscow eyes bank profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Oleg Soskovets, Russian deputy prime minister, yesterday floated the idea
of forcing banks to invest a fixed percentage of their profits in the
country's investment-starved industry. He told a banking conference that one
idea was to compel banks to sell 50 per cent of their profits from
'speculative' hard currency operations to the state. He gave no details,
although this would only generate a profit if the banks were not paid the
full market rate or were not paid on time.
The proposal, which was dismissed by Mr Victor Gerashchenko, central bank
chairman, as unlikely to work, provided the latest evidence of the
government's mixed instincts on market reform. Until now, it has talked of
the need for tax incentives and lower inflation to encourage capital
investment. At the same time, it has been discouraging investment through
frequent tax increases and changes in legislation.
</TEXT>
