<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 94 / Strong retail sales dash hopes of early reduction in rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strong growth in UK retail sales in March was yesterday seen as further
evidence of a buoyant economic recovery, reducing the chance of an early cut
in base rates.
The volume of retail sales grew by 0.8 per cent between February and March,
compared with market expectations of a 0.3 per cent rise. February's monthly
fall in sales was revised to 0.3 per cent, from the 0.5 per cent reported
earlier. The changes mean retail sales in March were 3.8 per cent higher
than a year earlier, against a revised figure of 2.8 per cent for February.
The figures follow the decline in unemployment, announced on Wednesday, and
an upbeat survey from the British Chambers of Commerce. Mr John Major, the
prime minister, told parliament that 'we are poised for a long period of
sustained, non-inflationary growth'.
However, the strength of the economy appeared to make it less likely that Mr
Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of
England, would agree to a further cut in base rates.
'Combined with the other recent signs of robust recovery - manufacturing
output, unemployment, business surveys - and the upward revision to average
earnings growth in January and February, these figures mean that an early
base rate cut is effectively ruled out,' said Mr Adrian Cooper, UK economist
at James Capel.
The figures came as something of a surprise after the Confederation of
British Industry published a downbeat survey of the distributive trades
sector earlier this week. This indicated annual retail sales growth in March
was slow, as it had been in February.
Analysts said that Easter, which straddled March and April this year, may
have distorted the seasonal adjustment of the official figures. This may
mean that sales will fall back this month when, in addition, the tax
increases take effect.
Mr Hugh Clark, trading policy director of the British Retail Consortium,
said: 'The CSO results confirmed our views that March was an excellent month
for retail sales. Trading was better than might have been expected in the
light of pending tax increases.'
