<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: Pirelli cuts loss to L96bn and
sees profit for 1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Pirelli, the Italian tyres and cables group, yesterday reported that its net
losses narrowed in 1993 to L96bn (Dollars 57m), compared with L154bn of
losses in 1992, and reinforced its earlier forecasts of a return to net
profit in 1994.
The more positive attitude at Pirelli follows three years of net losses, and
more than two years of painful restructuring. In 1992-93, Pirelli set aside
L550bn to pay for rationalisation, including 10,000 redundancies and the
shedding of one of its three divisions.
Yesterday's statement said the return to profit would still depend on the
level of recovery in the company's principal market, but the group reported
that it was making profits at operating level - L32bn in 1993, compared with
a loss of L93bn in 1992. Group sales in 1993 rose 12 per cent to L9,210bn
compared with L8,252bn.
The group was pushed into net loss last year by extraordinary charges of
L128bn. That included the extraordinary profit on last April's sale of
Pirelli's 33.4 per cent stake in Continental, its German rival, which was
not enough to offset restructuring provisions. At the time, the profit on
the Continental sale was estimated at L140bn, but Pirelli did not break down
the extraordinary items into individual gains and losses yesterday. The
group expects provisions over the last two years to cover all foreseeable
restructuring.
Mr Marco Tronchetti Provera, Pirelli's managing director, first expressed
his optimism about a profitable 1994 at the end of March when the company
announced plans to raise L1,000bn for expansion, through a convertible
debenture loan.
Shareholders will vote on those plans at their annual meeting on May 25.
</TEXT>
