<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nervousness again pervaded stock index futures which dragged down the cash
market as the June contract dipped below the psychologically important 3,100
level, writes Christine Buckley.
Although the June contract on the FT-SE 100 began trading firmly and climbed
to its intraday high of 3,156 early in the session, sentiment proved weak
for the rest of the day.
One derivatives specialist blamed a high level of proprietary trading and
panic selling for the volatility which is seeming to defy reason.
Curiously, selling of the contract set in shortly after the small cut in the
German repo rate was announced. Then the higher than expected rise in
average earnings sent June heading south fast to fall below 3,100.
'It is almost as though people have given up thinking,' said the specialist.
June struggled with the 3,100 mark throughout the session, constantly
slipping beneath it. Its lowest point was 3,092 and it closed at 3,094 with
a pick-up in turnover on recent sessions to reach 16,378 contracts.
Options were steady with 36,948 lots traded.
In a fast market, which has affected futures trading recently, all
operations of Liffe - including the clearing house system - operate as
usual, except screen prices are not firm.
