<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow slips over concern about
interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks retreated yesterday amid concern that the uptrend in interest
rates could harm corporate profits, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 21.11 lower at 3,598.71, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 2.17 at 441.96. Declining
issues led advances, 1,405 to 811, in heavy volume of 362m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite dropped 3.50 to 427.60,
and the Nasdaq composite lost 7.33 to 705.52.
The volatility of prices during the session again revealed an underlying
ambivalence among investors about the economic outlook. At the opening
shares surged by more 20 points ahead of news of a strong rebound in the
housing sector last month.
The Commerce Department said that housing starts in March had jumped 12.1
per cent, after an 8 per cent fall the previous month. The data suggested
the industry recovered well from February's weather-induced contraction.
The US Treasury market reacted calmly to the news. Bond prices improved
steadily during the day.
By contrast, the equitymarkets had a sudden shift in mood. Investors
appeared to be concerned that the surge in interest rates over the lasttwo
months would soon begin to harm corporate profitability, despite a strong
first quarter.
Caterpillar plunged Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 103 7/8 even though its
first-quarter performance was outstanding. It posted net income of Dollars
1.89 a share, against 34 cents a year ago.
For the second day, Chrysler was punished for failing to outperform
expectations for the quarter. It lost Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 46 after
shedding Dollars 2 3/8 the previous session.
Fears of an economic slowdown also hurt Ford, which dropped Dollars 2 1/8 to
Dollars 54 1/8 .
Some companies were rewarded after showing improvement. Compaq surged nearly
Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 101 7/8 after announcing a 95 per cent increase in
earnings. Bell Atlantic gained Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 53 3/4 as results
came in slightly ahead of forecasts.
Canada
Share prices fell slightly in moderate trading, extending the Toronto
market's losing streak to four straight sessions. The TSE 300 composite
index was off 9.14 points, or 0.22 per cent, at 4,105.93, with declines
leading advances 440 to 294.
Volume fell to 60.83m shares from 75.26m shares yesterday and trading value
declined to CDollars 712.7m from CDollars 850.5m.
Mexico
The stock market's key IPC index finished down 107.44 points, or 5.2 per
cent, at 1,957.33 - the third largest decline this year.
The dramatic fall was triggered by a surprisingly sharp rise earlier in
domestic short-term interest rates, traders said. The 28-day Cete rate was
raised by 342 basis points to 18 per cent.
The Ministry of Finance, meanwhile, said foreign institutions - including
banks, brokerage firms and insurance companies - would be allowed to begin
operating in Mexico in the second half of 1994.
</TEXT>
