<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Elections hit SA mines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Output from all South African mines was falling because of the first
all-party elections, Mr Gary Maude, chairman of Gengold, the country's
third-largest gold producer, said yesterday. Another Gengold official
estimated that gold production was down by as much as 5 per cent in the
first quarter.
'This is not a conscious go-slow,' said Mr Maude. 'But there is an expectant
atmosphere and people are not working with their usual concentration.' There
had also been a unusual rash of wildcat strikes about industry issues over
which mine managers had no influence.
All Gengold mines will shut on April 26, the first election day. Mr Maude
said there might be increased militancy after the elections but he felt sure
that the new government would want to ensure a continued flow of revenues
from gold.
