<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: Gengold drops 5.2% to R106m in
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK SUZMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An unsettled labour force in the run-up to South Africa's first all-race
elections was responsible for a 5.2 per cent drop in production for the
March quarter at Gengold, the gold mining division of South Africa's Gencor
group.
However, a higher gold price meant that after-tax profit declined only 3 per
cent to R106m (Dollars 20m), compared with R110.5m in the preceding three
months, and was still sharply up on the R75.3m for the same period last
year.
Due to reduced capital expenditure, distributable income rose from R78.2m to
R82.3m in the quarter, but total gold output declined to 15.87 tonnes from
16.7 tonnes in the December quarter as the effect of short strikes at a
number of the group's mines affected output. Overall gold yield remained
unchanged at 5.9 grammes/tonne.
The average gold price received was R39,663 a kg, well up on the previous
quarter's R37,992 but still short of the spot price as a result of the
group's hedging operations. However, Mr Tom Dale, general manager for
finance, said that no further hedging arrangements would be undertaken at
this stage and all forward sale contracts would be completed by May.
Of the group's big mines, Beatrix, Kinross and Winkelhaak mines all turned
in satisfactory performances, with Winkelhaak boosting after-tax income to
R12.9m from R9.3m.
The poorest results came from Buffelsfontein, which was affected by five
fires, three seismic events and a brief illegal strike. Production dropped
to 3,080 tonnes from 3,500 tonnes in the December quarter.
See Commodities
</TEXT>
