<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: WMX Technologies slides on
static sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WMX Technologies, the US waste management and environmental group, yesterday
reported a decline in first-quarter earnings to Dollars 162.6m, or 34 cents
a share, from Dollars 199.2m, or 41 cents, in the same 1993 quarter.
Sales were little changed at Dollars 2.3bn, against Dollars 2.1bn a year
ago. The group continued to suffer from the negative effects of weakness in
the hazardous waste disposal industry, the company said.
WMX is the parent company of Chemical Waste Management, Rust International,
Wheelabrator Technologies and Waste Management International.
Chemical Waste Management saw first-quarter earnings drop substantially to
Dollars 9.8m, from Dollars 21.3m in the first quarter of 1993.
'Conditions in the hazardous waste industry remain difficult. However, the
company is on schedule with its restructuring programme and continues its
efforts to lower costs,' said Mr Dean Buntrock, WMX chairman.
He said first-quarter earnings in all subsidiaries were hit by severe winter
weather. However, Mr Buntrock was confident of better trading during the
rest of this year.
</TEXT>
