FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: Canadian assurers may link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Great-West Life and Confederation Life, Canada's third and fourth-biggest
life assurers, are negotiating an alliance under which Great-West could end
up with a substantial stake in Confederation.
Confederation, hit in recent years by heavy losses on its mortgage
portfolio, said the talks were aimed at strengthening its capital base and
creating a 'strategic alliance'. No details have been disclosed.
The talks underline the upheaval in Canada's insurance sector, which has
been caused by competition from other financial institutions. Recent
regulatory reforms allow insurance companies to move into other sectors.
Great-West is 86 per cent owned by Power Financial, the Montreal-based
financial services group controlled by Mr Paul Desmarais. It posted a 72 per
cent rise in net income last year to CDollars 196m (USDollars 142m).
Great-West has assets of about CDollars 23bn. Confederation has assets of
about CDollars 20bn, but profits fell to CDollars 1.9m in 1992 from CDollars
105.7m in 1990.
