<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: Inco warns of need for
constraint on output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Inco, the world's biggest nickel producer, expects world supply and demand
for the metal to be roughly in balance by the second quarter of this year.
However, Mr Michael Sopko, chairman, indicated to the annual meeting in
Toronto yesterday that producers may have to cut output further to restore
equilibrium.
Mr Sopko singled out a continuing surge in exports from Russia, due mainly
to a collapse in domestic consumption, for over-supply in world markets.
However, he added: 'It is also up to the rest of us in the industry to take
responsible action to bring supply and demand into better balance.'
He insisted that Inco, which announced production cuts late last year, 'will
not shoulder the entire burden'. The company's priorities were 'to drive
down costs, improve our competitiveness and defend our market share'.
Inco suffered a first-quarter loss of USDollars 60.9m, or 53 cents a share,
up from Dollars 23.6m, or 22 cents, a year earlier. Revenues dropped to
Dollars 523.8m from Dollars 542.8m.
The latest losses reflect charges of Dollars 104m to cover the cost of staff
cuts and production shutdowns.
First-quarter nickel prices averaged Dollars 2.77 a pound, down from Dollars
2.95 a year earlier, but above the Dollars 2.42 realised in the final
quarter of 1993.
However, the market has weakened again recently in response to the rise in
North American interest rates and the collapse in Russian demand. London
Metal Exchange stocks have continued to rise. Nickel was trading yesterday
on the exchange at about Dollars 2.45.
