<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: Dior lifted by strong sales
growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Christian Dior, the French fashion house that holds a large minority stake
in the LVMH luxury goods group, yesterday announced a 9 per cent increase in
net profits to FFr876m (Dollars 148m) last year from FFr803m in 1992.
Mr Bernard Arnault, whose holding companies control both LVMH and Dior, said
that the latter was on course for large profits growth in 1994 if it could
sustain the strong sales growth shown in the first quarter. The board
proposed raising the net dividend to FFr9.00 from FFr8.40.
Dior, like other high fashion houses, was badly affected in the early 1990s
by the downturn in the global luxury goods market.
The company's net profits peaked at FFr5.3bn in 1989, two years before it
went public on the Paris stock market, and then fell steadily until the
increase last year.
However, the pressures on the international luxury goods industry have eased
recently.
Dior saw sales rise by 10 per cent to FFr24.62bn in 1993 from FFr22.4bn in
1992. The rate of sales growth accelerated towards the end of last year with
the upward trend continuing during the opening months of 1994. Dior's sales
rose by 27 per cent in February against the same month in 1993.
The old Dior fashion house last year produced a net profit of FFr116m.
However, the bulk of the company's profits, about FFr760m, came from the 25
per cent stake in LVMH held through its 55 per cent tranche of its Jacques
Rober subsidiary. Dior is expected soon to stage a capital increase
following the complex deal negotiated earlier this year by Mr Arnault to
unravel LVMH's cross-shareholding agreement with Guinness, the UK drinks
group.
</TEXT>
