<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / International Company News: USAir hit by low-fare rivals and
bad weather
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
USAir, the troubled US airline in which British Airways holds a 24.6 per
cent stake, yesterday reported net losses of Dollars 196.7m for the first
quarter. This compared with a loss of Dollars 61m for the same period in the
previous year before changes in accounting rules.
The group said it was seeking the agreement of its labour unions to an
Dollars 800m cost-cutting plan.
Early last month, USAir had warned it would report a loss of about Dollars
200m in the first quarter because of competition from low-cost rivals and
severe winter weather.
Yesterday, the company said about Dollars 50m of this year's first-quarter
loss resulted from weather-related flight delays and cancellations, implying
the rest was due to its inability to compete with low-fare rivals such as
Continental Airlines and Southwest Airlines.
British Airways has made clear to USAir that it is not prepared to invest
more money in its US partner until it has an effective cost reduction plan
and its financial performance improves.
USAir is the most heavily loss-making of all US airlines. It is the least
efficient, with unit costs of 11.3 cents per available passenger mile, more
than 25 per cent higher than the average recorded by the other big US
carriers last year.
Mr Seth Schofield, USAir's chairman and chief executive, told analysts he
wanted to get unit costs down to 10 cents a mile so the airline could better
compete with its low-cost rivals. That would mean an Dollars 800m-a-year cut
in its operating costs.
Part of these are expected to be secured through more efficient use of the
company's assets and employees - for example, by achieving faster turnround
times at airports. But most will have to come through labour concessions.
It said one option could be to offer employees shares in the company in
return for concessions, as several other US airlines have done.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>USAir Group Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
