<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / UK Company News: Recs line up Kleinwort for Grid sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The regional electricity companies yesterday set in motion a potential
disposal worth more than Pounds 1bn when they appointed Kleinwort Benson to
advise on the future of the National Grid, the power transmission company
which they own.
Yesterday's announcement was seen in the City as the precursor to a sale
next year of at least 25 per cent of the National Grid, the monopoly
transmitter of high voltage electricity in England and Wales.
The likely route is through a flotation on the Stock Exchange, although
Kleinwort Benson will look at other possibilities.
These could include issuing shareholders in the regional companies with
equity in the National Grid.
The Grid, which is setting up a telecommunications company, Energis, and is
looking for opportunities to expand abroad, is likely to be valued at about
Pounds 5bn.
Some analysts expect the sale of a second tranche of shares to be sold nine
months to a year after the initial disposal.
Yesterday's announcement said only that directors had decided to 'put in
hand a study of their options in relation to the future of the National Grid
Company.
'(They) have therefore appointed Kleinwort Benson and Herbert Smith (the
legal firm) to advise them.'
One regional power company chairman said last night it was possible the
study would result in no changes. 'We really do want to look at all the
options,' he said.
Analysts believe, however, that it is highly unlikely the regional power
companies will want to remain in control of all the shares in National Grid
as the general election approaches. The Labour Party has said in previous
elections that it wants the state to take control of the Grid.
That would be more difficult to achieve if share ownership were more
diversified.
The timing of any disposal will be influenced by the government's sale of
its 40 per cent stakes in National Power and PowerGen, the power generation
companies.
This is expected early next year but could be as soon as this autumn.
Kleinwort Benson, in conjunction with Barclays de Zoete Wedd, is advising
the government on the generator sales.
</TEXT>
