<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Schneider investigation will look at the role of banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Frankfurt state prosecutor's office is examining the role of the banks
in the collapse of the Jurgen Schneider property group last week.
Mr Hans-Hermann Eckert, a spokesman for the prosecuting authorities of the
state of Hesse, said he could not rule out the possibility that banks would
be suspected of 'involvement in fraudulent activity' or 'abetment to
fraudulent activity' in the case. The group went bankrupt with debts of
DM5bn (Pounds 2bn).
Mr Eckert made it clear the role of the banks would be examined in the
investigation into the affairs of Mr Jurgen Schneider, the property
entrepreneur whose disappearance two weeks ago triggered the crisis at the
group which bears his name.
Deutsche Bank, the German bank which is the largest creditor to the
Schneider group with outstanding loans of DM1.2bn, said it welcomed the
state prosecutor's investigations as a means to clear up the Schneider fraud
case. It said it was confident the investigations would not yield any basis
for prosecution against the bank. The bank has already faced complaints from
prosecuting authorities that it withheld information after finding out about
Mr Schneider's departure on April 7, four days before the group's problems
were made public. This has been vigorously denied.
Separately yesterday, tenants of the prestigious Madler-Passage development
in the heart of the eastern German city of Leipzig, launched a legal action
against Mr Schneider.
The tenants, who rented from CIP, Mr Schneider's property agency, said they
had unknowingly made their monthly rental payments into an anonymous account
since 1992. An estimated DM3m was paid in each year, but none of the
payments can be traced, the tenants allege.
The claim follows Deutsche Bank's own legal action in which the bank alleged
that Mr Schneider had presented it with fraudulent information when making
an application for credit to finance the Zeilgalerie shopping development in
the Frankfurt city centre.
Mr Schneider's whereabouts were still unclear yesterday despite claims by
Die Welt newspaper that he was on a small island near Sarasota on the coast
of Florida.
