<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Bimec gives up struggle to survive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bimec Industries, once a stock market favourite for its focus on
environmental services, yesterday gave up the struggle for survival just
eight months after bankers agreed a Pounds 13m rescue.
Despite three restructurings in six years, and the abrupt departure of its
controversial entrepreneur and chairman, Mr Sam Smith, the water and waste
treatment engineer called in accountants Arthur Andersen as administrative
receiver.
Mr Roy Barber, the company doctor appointed in 1992 who had previously
failed to save Astra Holdings, the munitions group linked to the Iraqi
supergun affair, said Bimec was unable to generate enough cash to carry it
through the summer.
The group's cash resources were almost Pounds 4m below target due to several
unexpected difficulties, including a payment dispute with the UK government,
delays on a water treatment contract in Belize and a shortfall in disposal
proceeds.
Lloyds Bank said yesterday it had refused to increased facilities following
an investigation by Arthur Andersen, jointly commissioned from Bimec and the
bank. The report concluded Bimec would need at least a further Pounds 2m in
working capital, which it could not repay.
In August, Lloyds agreed a refinancing in which it wrote off Pounds 5m in
debt and converted a further Pounds 3.5m into an 8 per cent stake in Bimec.
The bank had also provided a Pounds 5m working capital facility, which was
increased to Pounds 7.5m this year.
Bimec's total exposure to Lloyds is about Pounds 10m, of which about Pounds
7m is secured. Trade creditors are estimated at a further Pounds 7m.
Two of the group's profitable subsidiaries, Three Star Engineering and Dewey
Water, are not in receivership. These companies will be sold.
The group's difficulties date back to Mr Smith's chairmanship, when the
company sought to build its environmental business through acquisition to
take advantage of the newly-privatised water industry.
However, last year Mr Barber reported losses of Pounds 27m, after a Pounds
10.9m write-off to cover the overstatement of past profits. Bimec had
launched proceedings to sue the former auditors Grant Thornton for
negligence. The receivers are expected to examine the case.
</TEXT>
