<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Barclays Bank
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Martin Taylor's first management changes at Barclays Bank are gentler
than many had expected. He has not wielded the hatchet, which might have
damaged morale throughout the organisation. The new structure contains the
seeds of something radical just the same. One can quibble about the
uncomfortable position of the UK corporate business division suspended
between the clearing bank and BZW, and about the awkward dual reporting line
of its boss, Mr Graham Pimlott. But the new structure, which will eventually
be reflected in the segmental breakdown of the bank's accounts, will give
group management a better idea of how different parts of the group are
performing. It will also assist in the efficient allocation of capital to
the group's various activities. That will shed light on the overall capital
ratio that Barclays requires, a question which Mr Taylor re-opened soon
after his arrival. He is probably right to argue that more internal
competition for capital could be desirable in a market where slack loan
demand means banks' capital resources are not being stretched.
The more difficult decisions may come as the new structure beds down and the
group can discern which of its parts are delivering real value. Despite the
fanfare with which they were unveiled, Mr Taylor's changes only represent a
good start. More will be needed to keep up the momentum in Barclays' share
price which has out-performed the sector only modestly since his appointment
last August.
</TEXT>
