<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Volvo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Volvo's clean break with its previous chairman's ambition to form a
diversified holding group is welcome. The decision to dispose of interests
in BCP, the consumer products company, and Pharmacia, the pharmaceutical
group, and focus on the motor industry brings to an end a 20-year odyssey
that has included dabbling in crunchy cucumbers, North Sea oil and
stockbroking. The holding company strategy made little sense. Success in
automobiles requires focus. Though the earnings of a single-minded Volvo
will be more volatile, investors are quite capable of constructing
diversified portfolios for themselves.
That does not mean Volvo's new strategy will easily bear fruit. While its
truck operations are strong, it has few comparative advantages in cars. Even
its reputation for safety is being compromised by a marketing campaign
stressing Volvo's aggressive image. The big weakness remains the Swedish
company's insufficient size to earn a good return on investment in new model
development.
Volvo plans to overcome this weakness by forming ad hoc co-operative
ventures with other manufacturers. Such an approach may seem an attractive
way of maintaining independence following the Renault trauma. But it is
doubtful whether Volvo can cut costs and extend its market reach
sufficiently by a piecemeal strategy. With up to Skr40bn coming from the
non-core disposals, getting the cash to invest in cars will not be a
problem. The concern is rather that without effective collaboration that
cash will be frittered away.
</TEXT>
