<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Leading Article: Procter and guess what
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The financial news has acquired a distinctly gamey flavour of late. The
Granite group of hedge funds disappears with Dollars 600m of investors'
money; a top bond trader at US investment bank Kidder Peabody turns out to
have invented Dollars 350m of phantom profits to swell his profit-related
bonus; Bankers Trust sees its trading income collapse from Dollars 449m in
the final quarter of 1993 to a mere Dollars 14m in the first quarter of this
year and is under attack from Procter &amp; Gamble over advice on derivatives.
Is this par for the course, nowadays, in high finance and banking? Or is
something novel afoot?
Whatever the details of the particular stories, the principles involved are
not notably new. Granite owed its problems to a combination of excessive
borrowing and poor financial control over complex investment strategies.
Kidder Peabody has simply been the victim of old-fashioned fraud. As for
Bankers Trust, it is one of many banks where trading profits have been hit
by the fall in global bond markets.
From the point of view of banking supervision, the accelerating rate of
financial innovation may pose problems, but the nature of the risk involved
is entirely familiar. In the main, new instruments like derivatives are
designed to isolate or combine existing risks. In most cases that means
market risk, credit risk or something akin to the risk in insurance
underwriting. If there is a novel aspect in recent events, it may lie more
in a change in the structure of the banking industry itself.
Potential conflicts
Over the past decade or so the proprietary trading activities of wholesale
commercial and investment banks have come to account for a disproportionate
amount of their activity and profit. After a realistic allocation of costs
and provisions, it is in some cases a bigger contributor to profits than net
interest income. Financial intermediation - the task of taking deposits and
lending - has become less profitable and has been shrinking in importance.
Part of the dealing is conducted on behalf of clients, though some consists
of low-risk arbitrage. Yet while bankers tend to talk of their trading
activity as though it is largely to do with servicing their clients, it
appears increasingly to be about looking after themselves. The first-quarter
reports of the US money centre banks have demonstrated the importance of
proprietary trading. In effect, banks are becoming less like banks and more
like marketmakers. As a result, their income must be declining vastly in
quality.
One implication is that banks are involved in potential conflicts of
interest on a much greater scale than their clients have been used to. The
extent of the conflict has probably not always been fully appreciated by the
customers where, as in derivatives, the subject of the banks' advice is
highly complex. And the conflict can be heightened where company financial
executives are no match for much higher-paid, Harvard-educated whizz-kids
from the investment banking fraternity.
Better solution
In wholesale markets, caveat emptor provides a better solution to the
clients' problem than regulation. With derivatives, as with all financial
innovation, there is a learning curve. The bank supervisors' problem may be
another matter. For while the risks in derivatives may fall into familiar
categories, the language and techniques do not. The old men who run the
world's biggest banks do not understand vega and theta, kurtosis parameters
and volatility smiles.
Auditors cannot understand risk in over-the-counter instruments without a
degree of co-operation from traders that flies in the face of the
conventional arm's-length relationship with the audit client. The strength
of the intermediate balance sheets in global markets that connect large
numbers of parties to a given trade may not be known.
There may well be systemic shocks. And the growth of trading activity tends
to strengthen the case for dividing the banking system into a low-risk,
low-return sector covered by deposit insurance and an uninsured higher risk
sector for those who wish to deposit money with banks that have acquired a
penchant for gambling. Taxpayers should not be forced to underwrite the high
rollers of the banking system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
