<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Observer: Bell's clanger
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
John Major is not the only one on the receiving end of serious flak for the
shambles over how to celebrate the 50th anniversary of D-day. Sir Tim Bell,
Lady Thatcher's favoured public relations guru, has seen his reputation in
Whitehall plummet as the din over commemoration of the Normandy landings has
increased.
It was Bell - for a trifling Pounds 60,000 of taxpayers' money - who
suggested that nationwide street parties and spam-fritter frying contests
would provide a suitable tribute.
When protesting veterans said such events trivialised a battle which saw the
death of 37,000 allied soldiers, the complaints were initially dismissed as
'their problem'.
Now it is Sir Tim's problem - if the fulminations of one leading minister
are to be believed.
</TEXT>
