<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Observer: Bubbles
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is the Veuve Clicquot Business Woman of the Year award in danger of losing
its fizz? After 21 years of boosting female executives, it's beginning to
look almost as accident-prone as the now defunct Guardian Young Businessman
of the Year scheme.
Remember Sir Clive Sinclair, John Gunn of British and Commonwealth and John
Ashcroft of Coloroll? They got their GYB gongs and then fell flat on their
faces. The casualty rate among the bubbly businesswomen of the year is not
quite as high but it's starting to cause some concern.
Mair Barnes (1988 winner) resigned all of a sudden in February after seven
good years as managing director of Woolworths. Other honourable mentions go
to Debbie Moore (1983), whose Pineapple empire called in the receivers last
year owing upwards of Pounds 1m, and Sophie Mirman (1987), founder of Sock
Shop, who emerged from the attentions of administrators with only a small
children's wear chain.
But top marks surely go to Ann Iverson, who made it to the short list of
five for the 1993 awards, to be presented today. With cavalier disregard for
the champagne-maker's feelings, Iverson chucked in her job at Mothercare
earlier this week.
</TEXT>
