<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Economic Viewpoint: 'Competitiveness' rides again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What do you do if a confused idea has a seemingly irreversible hold on
politicians and businessmen? Oppose it to the bitter end, saying in
adaptation of King Lear: 'No sense will come from nonsense: speak again
prime minister'? Or redefine the idea to mean something sensible?
The first attitude describes the reaction of the Treasury's economic
thinkers to the UK government's promise or threat to publish a
'competitiveness' white paper on May 16 (a deadline likely to be missed).
The second is the alternative preferred by thinkers at the Department of
Trade and Industry, who would like to redefine competitiveness to mean
overall economic performance.
My sympathies are with the doubters. Competitiveness is a concept that
applies to companies, not countries. The interests of Coca-Cola and
Pepsi-Cola are in conflict, as one gains largely at the expense of the
other. The economic interests of the US and Japan, or of the European Union
and post-communist Europe, are not.
There is a limited meaningful sense in which one can talk about an
individual nation being uncompetitive. It may have cost levels at prevailing
exchange rates which are so high as to undermine the solvency of otherwise
profitable companies or to threaten jobs which would otherwise be safe. It
is in this sense that the UK was seen as uncompetitive at the 1990-92 ERM
exchange rate.
Uncompetitiveness here means an overvalued exchange rate. It is rarer than
supposed. Not every country can have an overvalued exchange rate. Moreover,
if a country has repeatedly depreciated, and the benefits are repeatedly
offset by rising domestic costs, then its problems are not those of
competitiveness even in the narrow, parochial sense, but of a different kind
 -often labour market ones.
The well-known US economist, Professor Paul Krugman, diagnoses the European
unemployment problem: 'Taxes and regulations imposed by Europe's elaborate
welfare states have made employers reluctant to create new jobs, while a
generous level of unemployment benefits has made workers unwilling to accept
the kind of low wage jobs that help keep unemployment comparatively low in
the US.' These difficulties are, he thinks, aggravated by exchange rate
links with post-unification Germany.
The British government would be in broad agreement with Krugman's diagnosis;
and even Jacques Delors came to adopt some of it in later versions of his
white paper. But both have done so under the misleading slogan of
safeguarding European competitiveness.
Indeed I have been provoked to return to the issue by the UK government's
efforts to make 'competitiveness' the focus of its economic policies.
Another influence has been that of Krugman, who has delivered what in a
logical world would be a knock-out blow to the idea in an article in the
April issue of Foreign Affairs and in a very entertaining book called
Peddling Prosperity, already published by Norton in the US and to be issued
in the UK on June 1 at the bargain price of Pounds 16.95.
One puzzle is how the European Union, whose currencies float against the
rest of the world, can be uncompetitive even in the narrow overvaluation
sense. John Major had a very good try at persuading EU summit conferences
that it was in 1993. But as I pointed out in an Economic Viewpoint of July 1
last, he based himself on a Commission chart of European unit labour costs
compared with US and Japanese ones, which contained a howler. For it was
drawn up in national currencies without correcting for exchange rates. When
this correction was made, it showed that both the US and the European Union
costs had risen less than Japan's.
Krugman comments: 'How could John Major, with the sophisticated resources of
the UK Treasury behind him, present an analysis that failed to make the most
standard of adjustments?' Scarcely credible as it may seem, the same chart,
without the exchange rate correction, was repeated in a 1994 UK paper,
Competitiveness and Employment.
In his efforts to be fair, Krugman tries to squeeze another meaning out of
'lack of competitiveness'. This is when deteriorating terms of trade are
required to price a country's goods into overseas markets. Krugman examines
an official US index called 'Command GNP', which corrects for terms of trade
effects and is thus an index of the nation's purchasing power. The
correction makes a trivial difference to the US trend.
I have replicated his analysis with the aid of the official index of UK
'Gross National Disposable Income'. This corrects the GNP estimates for
terms of trade effects and other modest complications. Over the whole period
1971-93 and even sub-periods, the movement of the two series was, as in the
US, almost identical.
The result is pretty remarkable for an exposed country with an overseas
trade sector three times as large as that of the US. But in both countries
exchange rate changes mainly offset inflation differentials and did not have
any noticeable effect on living standards.
British experience following the departure from the ERM in September 1992
does show some, probably temporary, departure from trend, but of an opposite
kind to that envisaged by pedlars of competitiveness. For the UK, terms of
trade have improved radically since ERM departure. If the official estimates
are to be believed, import prices have risen by 6 per cent, but export
prices by 17 per cent. Exporters have been criticised for raising margins
rather than reducing foreign currency prices. But if prices were already in
line with world markets, they have moved quite rationally to prevent their
products from becoming too 'competitive'.
Why does the rhetoric of 'competitiveness' have so much appeal? Businessmen
have a comfortable feeling of understanding if they can believe 'what is
good for General Motors is good for America'. Moreover, the images of the
'strategic traders' (those who sell competitiveness slogans in the US) are
bloodthirsty and thrilling, eg 'The decisive war of the century has begun
and America may already have decided to lose'.
A further reason may be that 'competitiveness' is often confused with the
case for competition. The latter refers to the benefits of rival bidding by
companies for their customers' dollar or pound, for workers and for loanable
funds in the capital market. It is promoted by measures such as anti-trust,
the outlawing of price rings and union closed shops, and the removal of
barriers to international trade, none of which depends on treating
international trade as warfare.
But why not allow our leaders their rhetoric if they can use it for good
causes, such as reducing the US budget deficit or removing rigidities from
European labour markets?
Krugman suggests three reasons. First, it can result in wasteful government
spending. An example is the proposed focusing of US government-sponsored
research on manufacturing, because it is more open to foreign competition
than services. Second, it can lead to protectionism and trade wars. One only
has to look at the US attempts to impose specific import targets on Japan.
Third, and most important, by encouraging sloppy thinking it can undermine
policy on a much larger range of issues. For instance, Lawrence Summers, a
former colleague of Krugman's and himself a well-known economist, in his
capacity as under-secretary of the US Treasury, asserts that Japan's surplus
is a drag on world growth instead of a source of useful savings. In Britain,
the normally economically-literate Peter Lilley, the social security
secretary, talks of Europe's 'need to be 'competitive' with the rising
Tigers of Asia'. Quite apart from any effect on GNP, clear thinking is
worthwhile for its own sake.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
