<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Letters to the Editor: Sacrosanct dividend is weak ground on
which to fight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MICHAEL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Paddy Linaker's article, 'City must defend its capital position'
(Personal View, April 19), provided a good starting point for debating the
City's role in financing companies and its attitudes to dividends. It also
underlines the difficulties that institutions are going to face in coming up
with a unified approach.
Whatever the theoretical strength of the 'dividend discipline' argument, the
public perception is of rapacious institutions demanding dividends at the
expense of all else and of failing to take their share of the pain in
difficult times. In industries where margins and return on capital are
volatile, it is difficult to see why dividends should be held through the
downswing, especially if this is at the cost of investment in capital
equipment, R&amp;D and training - thereby diminishing future growth prospects.
The primary function of the stock market is to provide new capital to
finance growth, given that capital is finite and needs to be rationed
according to where it will earn the highest return.
The slightly quaint but durable share underwriting process in the London
market has proved highly effective in providing new capital even at times of
financial distress.
However, the notion that City institutions should encourage companies to
maintain dividends at all costs and then to pay those dividends back via an
equity issue seems iniquitous. It is also grossly tax inefficient.
The M&amp;G should be congratulated on encouraging the City to set the agenda in
the debate about savings and investment flows. However, if it chooses to
rally around the banner of sacrosanct dividends, it will be fighting on weak
ground.
Michael Taylor,
associate director, UK equities,
Royal Insurance Asset
Management,
Westgate House,
9 Holborn,
London EC1N 2QE
</TEXT>
