<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Letters to the Editor: No better in Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr STEVEN R HUGGINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I think that the article by Gerald Cadogan (Property, April 16/17) may
leave people with the impression that the system of home-buying in Scotland
is better than that in England and Wales.
It is neither better nor worse; it is equally deficient. True, there is no
gazumping, but the downside for the buyer in Scotland is as follows. The
great majority of homes are advertised for sale as 'offers over' a certain
amount. A closing date is announced for the offers, and each person
interested in the home must pay for a survey and then put in their offer -
in total ignorance of how much other offers are or how much is expected - by
the closing date. It is a blind bidding system with no negotiation. If your
bid is not the highest, your offer will almost certainly not be accepted and
you will have lost the money you paid for the survey - at least Pounds 100
for just a valuation survey. Blind bidding or gazumping, home-buying in
Britain is no joy.
Steven R Huggins,
ground floor right,
18 Balcarres Street,
Morningside,
Edinburgh EH10 5JD
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
