<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Letters to the Editor: Irrelevance of share options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr NIGEL DYCKHOFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I have read with interest the various articles and letters over the
past few months on the subject of share options.
Although the coverage has been virtually comprehensive, there are a couple
of vital points which have been overlooked. The first is that share options
have for some years been cynically regarded as 'a gamble to which executives
were entitled'. I think it is now questionable whether, in fact, share
options are necessarily any more a relevant method of reward. They obviously
had a place when executives had been highly taxed and found it almost
impossible to amass capital during their business career but now, like long
contracts and over-generous severance payments, they may no longer deserve
their place.
Second, if parity between executives and shareholders in the ownership of
their company is sought, then perhaps the old-fashioned route of loans to
purchase shares at full value and freedom to sell and buy to suit the
executive's personal circumstances might not be a bad way of ensuring
involvement.
Outstanding company performance may be better rewarded by cash bonuses paid
over the long term and directly and visibly linked to that performance.
Nigel Dyckhoff,
16 Connaught Place,
London W2 2ED
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
