<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GAY FIRTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Unashamedly biased. And unashamedly jaundiced.' John MacUre is the writer
of Cardiac Arrest (9.30 BBC1) a new six-part drama series about working in
the NHS, He adds: 'It is a tale that any junior doctor will tell.' He should
know - he is himself a practising junior doctor.
In the first episode, a young houseman's idealised sense of health care
buckles under the weight of a chaotic system trying to save lives -
including the NHS's. 'People will hope it is make-believe. But it's not,'
Doctor MacUre says bleakly. Oh, really? Tell us about it.
Before plunging into a sea of medical troubles, brace yourself with Class
Act (9.00 ITV), which continues the comic adventures of a mismatched trio
starring the lovely and talented Joanna Lumley. Romance is in the air this
evening - but is it the real thing? Who cares - Miss Lumley is real enough
for anyone to love.
And if you want to stick around long enough for another dose of professional
angst, Street Legal (12.35am ITV) is a Canadian drama series which follows
the personal and professional lives of four trial lawyers.
</TEXT>
