<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / The Queen's Awards 1994: Freezers of the frozen north -
Norfrost / James Buxton examines five companies which are leading Scotland's
export drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Norfrost is unusual not only for succeeding in an industry in which the UK
is not a substantial player, but for doing so from one of the most remote
locations in Britain - Caithness.
It makes chest freezers and coolers, which are used predominantly in shops
and businesses, as well as in private homes.
Last year its turnover was Pounds 24m, of which two-thirds was exported.
Seven years ago exports accounted for only eight per cent of much lower
sales.
Norfrost, a private company, says it exports to 80 countries, but entered 24
of them for the first time last year.
Norfrost is the creation of Mrs Pat Grant and her husband Alex who
established it in 1972. She supplies the entrepreneurial drive and he the
technical expertise which enables Norfrost to produce successful designs at
economic prices.
The company, which employs about 300 people, concentrates on only one basic
product which is assembled on a large production line.
Its freezers and coolers are basically the same: the only difference between
them is in the type of thermostatic controller.
Norfrost has major customers on its books. It supplies Coca-Cola with
coolers which the drinks company provides to retailers. It also sells to
manufacturers such as Zanussi and Hitachi which sell the machines under
their own labels.
Its largest markets are the US and France, as well as Germany, Italy, Japan,
Saudi Arabia, Egypt and eastern Europe.
After completing a three year Pounds 8m factory extension last year, Mrs
Grant announced further expansion plans which would create a minimum of 120
new jobs within the next two-and-a-half years. She hopes to employ 1,000
people by the end of the decade.
Mrs Grant's achievements have already been honoured by the Businesswoman of
the Year award 1988 and the Women Mean Business Award.
Part of Norfrost's achievement is in brushing off the disadvantages of its
remote location.
It does this through vertical integration: it makes its own production
tools, carries out its own maintenance and has its injection moulding
company.
To ensure that its trucks return fully laden, it provides a haulage service
for other businesses in Caithness.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Norfrost Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3582 Commercial Laundry Equipment.
    P3632 Household Refrigerators and Freezers.
</IN>
