<DATE>940421
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 94 / Political Notebook: Strategy of survival for Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At Westminster there is the uneasy calm of a phoney peace. In Downing Street
the atmosphere is strained. Mr John Major has six weeks to put in place a
strategy for survival.
Nobody at Westminster is quite sure what to expect from the local elections
on May 5 and the European elections on June 9. That the Tories will do badly
is taken for granted. The scale of defeat is harder to gauge.
But the anecdotal evidence is deeply depressing for the prime minister. Tory
MPs returning from the campaign trail say the party faithful are still
seething with resentment. Once-loyal activists are in no mood to be told
that better times are around the corner.
Local loyalties might blunt the disenchantment in the council elections. But
there seems a real prospect of a collapse in the Tory vote in the European
poll and the Eastleigh by-election. The possibility can no longer be
discounted that the party will be placed third in a national election for
the first time in living memory. The immediate aftermath of the European
poll will be the most dangerous moment of Mr Major's premiership. A formal
leadership challenge must wait until November. But the risk is of an
irresistible tide sweeping him from office during the summer.
Mr Major insists that nothing will shift him. But remember Margaret
Thatcher's words just a day before she was driven from Downing Street: 'We
fight on. We fight to win.'
So the focus of Mr Major's strategy for survival is to hold on in Downing
Street from June 9 until the summer recess in mid-July. A challenge in
November will have to be tackled if and when. There is a chance that by the
autumn economic recovery will have refloated his government.
To have a decent chance of surviving until then Mr Major has to do two
potentially contradictory things. He must maintain the visible loyalty of
his cabinet - it was the desertion of her colleagues which finished Mrs
Thatcher. But he must also shake up the government - and his own team of
personal political advisers - in a way which begins to rebuild his shattered
authority.
On paper Mr Major should have little trouble securing cabinet backing. Save
for the two leading contenders for the succession - Mr Kenneth Clarke and Mr
Michael Heseltine - most see a vested interest in sticking with the present
leader.
That might change swiftly if the election results trigger a collective
nervous breakdown on the back benches. Supporters of Mr Clarke and Mr
Heseltine are not alone in planning for other contingencies. Mr Michael
Portillo's friends have been testing his support on the back benches.
Mr Major has rejected advice to bring forward the cabinet reshuffle to
before June 9. Aides insist he will not be panicked and are talking in terms
of July. But it could come within a week or so of the European election if
the poll results are as bad as some fear.
Mr Major must make extensive - although not draconian - changes. He must
give the cabinet a sharper political edge, replacing administrators with
street-fighters.
Among the names already at the top of Downing Street promotion lists are Mr
Stephen Dorrell at the Treasury, Dr Brian Mawhinney at health, Mr Jonathan
Aitken at defence and Mr David Davis at public services.
In a government underburdened with talent all have a decent claim to seats
at the top table. Their elevation - and the sacking of a number of
middle-ranking timeservers - would make way for a wave of promotions from
the restless back benches.
The relative youth of the new team could be balanced by the return of one or
two heavyweights from the 1980s. The idea is a long shot, but Lord Howe
might calm a fractious House of Lords. If Mr Heseltine cannot be persuaded
to take the party chairmanship, Lord Walker might be the next best choice.
Mr Major has also been told in the strongest possible terms that he must
replace Mr Graham Bright, his lacklustre parliamentary private secretary,
with an adviser of stature and reputation in the Commons.
The common denominator linking those on the list of possible cabinet
departures is that they would be either unwilling or unable to damage Mr
Major from the back benches. Mr John MacGregor, Mr Peter Brooke, Mr John
Patten and Mr John Gummer would not become plotters.
Overall, the ideas now being floated have the makings of a credible if
less-than-fireproof strategy. But Mr Major, who sometimes appears at once
stubborn and indecisive, must strike the right balance between unaccustomed
boldness and more familiar panic.
</TEXT>
